            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Volkov\u2019s life has been a study in quiet intensity. Born in Boston to Soviet-era academics who had fled a collapsing system for intellectual freedom, he was raised in a home where dinner conversations revolved around scientific theory and classical literature. His father, a physicist, and his mother, a linguist, instilled in him a rigorous discipline and an insatiable curiosity. This upbringing shaped him into a focused, analytical young man who saw the world as a series of complex problems awaiting elegant solutions.\n\nHis path was clarified during his undergraduate studies at Johns Hopkins. His grandmother, a cherished link to his Russian heritage, was succumbing to Huntington's disease. Watching her decline ignited a fierce determination in Dmitri. He pivoted his focus to biotechnology, driven by a personal mission to untangle the genetic knots of neurodegenerative disorders. He earned his Master\u2019s from a top-tier program, publishing a paper that caught the attention of a leading research firm in South San Francisco.\n\nMoving to the Bay Area was a jarring but necessary transition. He traded the historic brick of the East Coast for the vibrant, chaotic energy of San Francisco. He found a small apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood whose fog and Russian bakeries offered a faint echo of a home he\u2019d never really known. His life is one of routine: an early morning Muni ride, losing himself in podcasts about genetic sequencing, followed by 10-hour days in the sterile, humming environment of the lab. His work on CRISPR-based therapies is his true passion, leaving little room for a sprawling social life.\n\nHis social circle is tight-knit, consisting of a few colleagues who share his obsessive drive and a climbing partner he meets weekly at a bouldering gym\u2014his one escape from the cerebral. Recently, he began dating a landscape architect named Maya, whose creative, unstructured view of the world both fascinates and slightly unnerves him.\n\nDmitri\u2019s dream is to one day lead a research team that pioneers a viable treatment for Huntington's. He feels a deep connection to San Francisco as the epicenter of his field, but the city's staggering cost of living feels like a constant, low-grade pressure. He wonders if his six-figure salary will ever be enough to build a permanent life here, or if, like his parents, his search for a solution will ultimately lead him somewhere new."
